  <span id="freeText8968906934452772052" style="display:none">I‚Äôm well aware of the privileges I hold simply by accident of birth. And I‚Äôm also aware that a turn of circumstance, like devastating illness or unemployment, could suddenly take away many of the comforts I take for granted.<br /><br />Esperanza is an adolescent girl who suddenly has to face a future where all the things in her life are suddenly taken away from her. It‚Äôs the story of her new perspective, her new path forward.<br /><br />It‚Äôs also a story of immigration, of racism, of classism, of family. It‚Äôs the story of migrant farm workers fighting for decent wages and humane working conditions.<br /><br />It‚Äôs a big, beautifully told story, full of hope, packed into a short novel.<br /><br />I especially liked the author‚Äôs afterword, where she talked about her own family history that inspired the book.<br /><br />And it‚Äôs very concerning that some of the worst attitudes and policies toward immigrants depicted in this book and in the afterword are being propagated again with a vengeance by our current administration.<br /><br />My daughter thought it was boring.</span>
